\n* Bazha ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5df4\u624e\u793e\u533a}}), Wenhua ({{lang|zh-hans|\u6587\u5316\u793e\u533a}}), Tuanjie ({{lang|zh-hans|\u56e2\u7ed3\u793e\u533a}})\n[[Village (China)|Villages]]:\n*Longga (Longgacun<ref name=\"GNISlg\">{{GEOnet2|6B4D1F6379FA185CE0535FB81CD602B1|Longgacun   (Approved - N)}}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref>; {{lang|ug|\u0644\u0648\u06ad\u06af\u0627 \u0643\u06d5\u0646\u062a\u0649}}<!--http://big5.cri.cn/gate/big5/wei6.chinabroadcast.cn/7466/more/20131/ZTmore20131.htm \u06af\u06c7\u0645\u0627 \u0646\u0627\u06be\u0649\u064a\u0649\u0633\u0649 \u0645\u06c7\u062c\u0649 \u0628\u0627\u0632\u0649\u0631\u0649 \u0644\u0648\u06ad\u06af\u0627 \u0643\u06d5\u0646\u062a\u0649 \u06cb\u06d5 \u0644\u06d5\u06ad\u06af\u06d5\u0631 \u0643\u06d5\u0646\u062a\u0649\u06af\u06d5 \u0686\u06c8\u0634\u0643\u06d5\u0646 \u062e\u0649\u0632\u0645\u06d5\u062a \u06af\u06c7\u0631\u06c7\u067e\u067e\u0649\u0633\u0649 \u0626\u0627\u067e\u062a\u0648\u0646\u0648\u0645 \u0631\u0627\u064a\u0648\u0646\u0644\u06c7\u0642 \u062c\u06c7\u06ad\u064a\u0649 \u062a\u06d0\u0628\u0627\u0628\u0649\u062a\u0649 \u062f\u0648\u062e\u062a\u06c7\u0631\u062e\u0627\u0646\u0649\u0633\u0649\u0646\u0649\u06ad ...--> / {{lang|zh-hans|\u9f99\u5c15\u6751}}), Langan ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5170\u5e72\u6751}}), Yingbage ({{lang|zh-hans|\u82f1\u5df4\u683c\u6751}}), Kuonasayibage ({{lang|zh-hans|\u9614\u7eb3\u8428\u4f9d\u5df4\u683c\u6751}}), Bashitiereke ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5df4\u4ec0\u94c1\u70ed\u514b\u6751}}), Hantuge ({{lang|zh-hans|\u6c57\u5410\u683c\u6751}}), Aziganbage ({{lang|zh-hans|\u963f\u5b5c\u5e72\u5df4\u683c\u6751}}), Gaziqiaka ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5c15\u5b5c\u6070\u5580\u6751}}), Muji ({{lang|zh-hans|\u6728\u5409\u6751}}), Kuonatugeman ({{lang|zh-hans|\u9614\u7eb3\u5410\u683c\u66fc\u6751}}), Sayi ({{lang|zh-hans|\u8428\u4f9d\u6751}}), Asa'er ({{lang|zh-hans|\u963f\u8428\u5c14\u6751}}), Kuonabazha ({{lang|zh-hans|\u9614\u7eb3\u5df4\u624e\u6751}}), Sayibage ({{lang|zh-hans|\u8428\u4f9d\u5df4\u683c\u6751}}), Ayagebagela ({{lang|zh-hans|\u963f\u4e9a\u683c\u5df4\u683c\u62c9\u6751}}), Bagela ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5df4\u683c\u62c9\u6751}}), Bashibagela ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5df4\u4ec0\u5df4\u683c\u62c9\u6751}}), Arejianggale ({{lang|zh-hans|\u963f\u70ed\u6c5f\u5c15\u52d2\u6751}})\n\n==Transportation==\n* [[China National Highway 315]]<ref name=\"1997xzqhguma\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Xinjiang]]\n[[Category:Township-level divisions of Xinjiang]]\n\n\n{{Xinjiang-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Geographyinitiative", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muji,_Xinjiang"}
{"title_page": "Pitsen", "text_new": "'''Pitsen''' <ref>also spelled bi\u00e7en, pichan, pechan, pitsin, picen, picin, yen, yenp\u00e4ri, Urman \u0130\u00e4se&nbsp;\u2013 the Host of the Forest; [[Cyrillic]]: \u041f\u0438\u0446\u0435\u0301\u043d.</ref> is a forest creature in the [[Siberian Tatars]]' mythology.\n\nPitsen's role is contradictory. It could bring luck, but also troubles, leading humans to the wilderness.\n\n[[Shapeshifting]] is common for Pitsen: he may look like an elder with a staff and knapsack, but also like different animals, for example [[apes]]. Pitsen prefers to live in derelict lodges. He also likes to ride horses and to oil their mane with tar.<ref name=\"waliev\">{{in lang|ru}} \u0412\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0435\u0432 \u0424. \u0422., \u041e \u0440\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0433\u0438\u043e\u0437\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0438\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0442\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0440, \u0432 \u0441\u0431.: \u041f\u0440\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0438 \u0447\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043a \u0432 \u0440\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0433\u0438\u043e\u0437\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0432 \u0421\u0438\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0438 \u0438 \u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0430, \u041b., 1976, \u0441. 320-29.</ref>\n\nPitsen, when transformed to a damsel, may have sexual intercourse or marry a human. One legend says that one hunter happened upon beautiful damsel in a forest and married her. Soon they become rich. Once he came home ahead of time and saw a tusky monster eating lizards. He cried, being horrified, and that moment his wife and his riches disappeared.<ref name=\"waliev\"/>\n\nPitsen is a counterpart of [[Chuvash people|Chuvash]] [[Archura|Ar\u00e7uri]] and Volga-Ural Tatar [[\u015e\u00fcr\u00e4le]]. In the mythology of the Siberian Tatars, Tobol and Omsk Tatars had shaggy and stinking ''yysh-keshe''.<ref>{{IPA-tt|j\u026f\u0283 k\u02b2e\u02c8\u0283e|}}</ref> They carry away travelers and force them to marry. At night the spirit of yysh-keshe used to fly away from an armpit.<ref name=\"waliev\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[\u015e\u00fcr\u00e4le]]\n*[[Yeti]]\n*[[Shapeshifting]]\n\n==References and footnotes==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Siberian Tatars]]\n[[Category:Shapeshifting]]\n[[Category:Turkic legendary creatures]]\n[[Category:Forest spirits]]\n", "text_old": "'''Pitsen''' <ref>also spelled bi\u00e7en, pichan, pechan, pitsin, picen, picin, yen, yenp\u00e4ri, Urman \u0130\u00e4se&nbsp;\u2013 the Host of the Forest; [[Cyrillic]]: \u041f\u0438\u0446\u0435\u0301\u043d.</ref> is a forest creature in the [[Siberian Tatars]]' mythology.\n\nPitsen's role is contradictory. It could bring luck, but also troubles, leading humans to the wilderness.\n\n[[Shapeshifting]] is common for Pitsen: he may look like an elder with a staff and knapsack, but also like different animals, for example [[apes]]. Pitsen prefers to live in derelict lodges. He also likes to ride horses and to oil their mane with tar.<ref name=\"waliev\">{{in lang|ru}} \u0412\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0435\u0432 \u0424. \u0422., \u041e \u0440\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0433\u0438\u043e\u0437\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0438\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0442\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0440, \u0432 \u0441\u0431.: \u041f\u0440\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0438 \u0447\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043a \u0432 \u0440\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0433\u0438\u043e\u0437\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0432 \u0421\u0438\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0438 \u0438 \u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0430, \u041b., 1976, \u0441. 320-29.</ref>\n\nPitsen, when transformed to a damsel, may have sexual intercourse or get married to a human. One legend says that one hunter happened upon beautiful damsel in a forest and married her. Soon they become rich. Once he came home ahead of time and saw a tusky monster eating lizards. He cried, being horrified, and that moment his wife and his riches disappeared.<ref name=\"waliev\"/>\n\nPitsen is a counterpart of [[Chuvash people|Chuvash]] [[Archura|Ar\u00e7uri]] and Volga-Ural Tatar [[\u015e\u00fcr\u00e4le]]. In the mythology of the Siberian Tatars, Tobol and Omsk Tatars had shaggy and stinking ''yysh-keshe''.<ref>{{IPA-tt|j\u026f\u0283 k\u02b2e\u02c8\u0283e|}}</ref> They carry away travelers and force them to get married. At night the spirit of yysh-keshe used to fly away from an armpit.<ref name=\"waliev\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[\u015e\u00fcr\u00e4le]]\n*[[Yeti]]\n*[[Shapeshifting]]\n\n==References and footnotes==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Siberian Tatars]]\n[[Category:Shapeshifting]]\n[[Category:Turkic legendary creatures]]\n[[Category:Forest spirits]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pitsen"}
